  "slug": "salmon-and-dill-pie",
  "title": "Salmon and Dill Pie",
  "subtitle": "Flaked salmon in a cream and dill sauce, topped with a golden puff pastry crust",
  "excerpt": "Salmon and dill are one of the most reliable flavour pairings in British cooking. This pie poaches salmon fillets in stock and white wine, flakes them into a thick cream and dill sauce, and finishes with a puff pastry lid baked until crisp and golden.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Traditional British fish pie. Jane Grigson, Fish Cookery (1973): salmon with cream sauce and herbs. Delia Smith, Complete Cookery Course (1978): fish pie with puff pastry. British summer entertaining tradition.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Salmon for a pie should be poached rather than roasted. A brief poach in a ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "court-bouillon",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpdr3vp00000hgv4dny1v396"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " of white wine and herbs leaves the flesh tender and the poaching liquid flavoured enough to become the sauce base. Flake the fish into large pieces rather than fine shreds; you want identifiable chunks of salmon in the finished pie.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "dill",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpdr3vpt0001hgv4trznrqtq"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " off the heat, after the sauce has finished cooking. Dill loses its fragrance quickly at high temperatures.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "What you need",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
