      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Poach the salmon",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Combine the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{white-wine-dry}} of white wine",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{stock-chicken}} of stock",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " in a wide saucepan. Bring to a simmer and lay in the salmon fillets skin-down. Poach for 6-8 minutes until the flesh just flakes at the thickest point. Remove the fish, peel away the skin, and flake into large pieces. Reserve the poaching liquid.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Build the sauce",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Melt ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{unsalted-butter}} of butter",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " in a saucepan. Stir in ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{plain-flour}} of flour",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and cook for 2 minutes. Gradually add the strained poaching liquid, stirring until smooth. Add ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{double-cream}} of cream",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and simmer until the sauce thickens to a consistency that coats a spoon heavily. Season with ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{sea-salt-flakes}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{black-pepper}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". Off the heat, stir in most of the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{dill}} of dill",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and the capers if using. Fold in the salmon. Cool completely.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Top and bake",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the oven to 200°C (180°C fan). Spoon the cooled filling into the pie dish. Lay the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{puff-pastry}} of puff pastry",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " over the top and press the edges to the rim. Score the surface lightly and cut a steam vent. Brush with beaten egg. Bake for 35-40 minutes until the pastry is deep golden and puffed. Rest for 5 minutes before serving.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "rows": [
            {
              "fix": "Use undiluted beaten egg. Check oven temperature with a thermometer. A further 10 minutes at 210°C will colour pale pastry.",
              "cause": "Oven temperature lower than expected, or egg wash was thin",
              "symptom": "Pastry is pale after 40 minutes"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Dampen the dish rim with water before pressing the pastry down. Crimp firmly with a fork.",
              "cause": "Pastry edge was not pressed firmly to the dish rim",
              "symptom": "Filling leaks out at the edges"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Always add dill off the heat, after the sauce has cooled to below simmering.",
              "cause": "Dill was added to the sauce while it was still very hot, destroying the volatile flavour compounds",
              "symptom": "Dill flavour is absent in the baked pie"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Poach just until the fish gives when pressed, not until it falls apart. Fold the fish in with one or two turns of a spatula.",
              "cause": "Overpoached or folded too vigorously",
              "symptom": "Salmon has broken down into a paste"
            }
          ]
        },
        "content": []
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Salmon and dill pie sits at the smarter end of the British fish pie repertoire. It is the kind of dish that appears at Easter lunches and summer weekend gatherings, made ahead, needing only the oven.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
